rency, public participation and tendering).</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1.5pt; margin:6pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">My background and this submission:</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Since 1992, I have practised as a barrist</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">er specialising in, among other things, education law. I have also been a member of a Local Education Authority, a governor at five schools and a Further Education College, and a part time judge of the Special Educational Needs and Disability Tribunal.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">the course of my practice as a lawyer I have advised and acted for (including in legal proceedings) a great many parents, parents’ groups, governing bodies, head teachers, unions, NGOs and local authorities on issues relating to school organisation/re-orga</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">nisation </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">and governance </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">including, in particular (since 2005) in relation to academies and free schools. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">I am the author of the blog on academies/free schools and the law: </span><a href="http://www.acanofworms.org.uk"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; text-decoration:underline">www.acanofworms.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> which has been</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> looked at by an average of over 1,000 people per week since I set it up in October 2011.</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1.5pt; clear:both; margin:6pt 0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:6pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">What follows is my summary response on each of the points I understand to be under consideration by the Select Committee. I have only commented on those things on whi</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">ch I have direct relevant expertise based on my personal experience</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> and focussed my points on legal/governance aspects</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:6pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">I would be very happy to elaborate as requested. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:6pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">I would be pleased to assist by giving oral evidence to the Committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“The </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes;”</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">No comment</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“The process for approving, compell</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">ing and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors;”</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="font-size:13pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Academy conversion</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">At present, there are three streams of maintained school becoming </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; text-decoration:underline">academies</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> (I will deal with free schools below) which all raise different issues:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 68.51pt; padding-left:3.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">‘rewarded succeeders’ </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 69.11pt; padding-left:2.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">‘punished failures’</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">‘near boiled frogs’</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“Rewarded succeeders”</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> are those schools whose governing bodies</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">, because of Ofsted success</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> are allo</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">wed </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">to convert to become freestanding academies (with the governing body setting up the </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Academy Trust which then enters into the Funding Agreement</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> with the Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">).</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> They are then freestanding legal entities under the long term control of Trustees appointed by that predecessor Governing Body. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Although the Governing Body is require</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">d (by the Academies Act 2010) to undertake consultation on whether conversion should go ahead</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">, that process is generally undertaken at a stage when t</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">he Governing Body has, in reality</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">, made up its mind </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">(to go ahead with conversion) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">and it is rarely perceive</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">d (to say the least) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">by parents and other stakeholders </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">amount </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">to a transparent</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">, open m</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">inded and participative process</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">. That </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">can lead to huge, and potentially unnecessary, fracturing and dispute within school communities</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> which is not helpful</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“Punished </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">failures”</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> are those schools where (the school having become ‘eligible for intervention’) an Academy Order is made (and then a Funding Agreement signed) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">to create a ‘sponsored academy’ (with an imposed sponsor) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">in the face of opposition from the governing b</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">ody of the maintained school (sometimes with the installation of an IEB which then promotes the conversion).</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Issues includ</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">e: the process of choosing a sponsor (which lacks transparency and openness to say the least), </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">let alone </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">any meaningful public proces</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">s which properly contemplates </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">(among other things) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">any alternative to conversion as the way to deal with the issues faced by the school (which is particularly ironic where an IEB is involved since the legal framework which underpins IEBs gives them the rol</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">e of taking steps to enable the restoration of a normal governing body in the maintained school, rather than the role they are here being appointed to do, which is to steer an academy conversion.)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“Near boiled frogs”</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> are schools where the governing body in</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">itiates the conversion process </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">to become a ‘sponsored academy’ ahead of (say) an Ofsted inspection in the hope that that will give it greater influence in the process (eg choice of sponsor) than would be the case if the school was to become eligible for in</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">tervention and </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">thus </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">have a sponsor imposed. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">I have drawn the term from the image painted by a DfE academy broker to a meeting of governors: “Think of yourselves as a frog in a pan of water on the </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">stove. You can wait for the flames of Ofsted to bring the w</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">ater to the boil, or jump out now while you still can. I would advise you to jump now.”</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Issues include the pressure put on </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">(and sometimes clear misinformation provided to) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Governing Bodies by the DfE </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">(or its ‘brokers’) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">to vote early in the process to invi</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">te the making of an Academy Order (following which the process is entirely out of their hands) and what, in practice, turns out to be only a very limited ability to influence the selection of the sponsor. That coupled with the same issues of lack of partic</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">ipation </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">etc.</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> in the process which arise above.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Sponsors</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">The term ‘sponsor’</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> (and similar)</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">along with the associated use of the language of ‘partnership’</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> is in my view very misleading. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">In particular, </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">they imply</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> a relationship between two entities </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">(partners?) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">which </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">is not the case. </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">That is because a</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> sponsored academy </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">(or one in a ‘chain’) </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">has no separate legal status – it is merely the local branch/site through which the ‘sponsor’ </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">or chain </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">provides education pursuant to its Funding Agreement with t</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">he Secretary of State. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">One of the consequences of that is that the ‘governing body’ (often called the ‘local governing body’) of an academy which is sponsored or in a chain almost invariably has </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; text-decoration:underline">fewer</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> powers and </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; text-decoration:underline">less</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> independence/autonomy than did/would t</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">he governing body of maintained school. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">In practice, such ‘independence’ as comes with academy </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">status</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">’ as such</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> lies with the sponsor/chain and </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> with the individual school (its governing body or head teacher). The school is only free to act within the </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">constraints set by the chain/sponsor (when it comes to curriculum, uniform, staff/employment issues, budget/finance issues, school policies, and so on). </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">It is as if the clock has been put back to the 1980s (before ‘local management’ of schools, let alone </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">‘delegated budgets’) when schools needed </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">local education authority </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">decision </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">on almost every point. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">In practice, there has </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">thus </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">been a real loss of ‘independence’ despite the contrary claim. That is ironic given that (for example) DfE ‘academy brokers’</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> continue to describe the process to schools as giving them ‘freedoms’ and ‘independence’. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Certainly, it </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; text-decoration:underline">cannot</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> be said governing bodies now retain what was previously identified as their core roles: </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">setting </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">the vision, ethos and strategic direction</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> of th</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">eir school</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">performance management of the head teacher</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">and ensuring</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">the sound, proper and effective use of the school’s finances</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:13pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Free schools</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Some free schools are standalone academies. Others are local branches of </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">academy/free school </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">chains.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Issues include the lack of any transparent process for allowing alternative promoters (let alone alternative school models) to come forward for consideration where a </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">new </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">school has been identified as necessary to meet a local shortfall of places.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">And also,</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> of course, the bigger problem of free schools being promoted/permitted </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">where there is already a local surplus of school places the effect of which is to reduce the resources available to other schools and thus to diminish their ability to (say) deliver a </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">wide range of curriculum choices. In effect, a ‘choice’ [sic] of schools is being created but at the expense of curriculum choice (</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">etc.</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">) within existing schools. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">The funding arrangements for free schools (particularly i</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">n their early days) also remain</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> comp</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">letely opaque, with free schools doing their best to resist providing information on, for example, the extent to which they are being funded on a ‘level playing field’ basis with other schools including (for example) even whether they are being funded by r</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">eference to the number of pupils they predicted they would recruit</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> or the (much lower) number they </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">have </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">actually recruited. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Ironically, free schools are claiming ‘commercial confidentiality’ in such funding information in a way which would not be possibl</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">e for a maintained school.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands;”</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Each academy is, in legal/ terms, very much the product of the time and circumstance o</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">f its creation. That is because, among other things, funding agreements are based on the model of the time (which has changed over time), there are variants in the circumstance of creation (as above), and where an academy/free school is part of a chain or </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">similar the division of governance responsibilities between the centre and the local academy is a matter for the local arrangements</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> (with the entire governance framework being dependent on the particular sponsor)</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">However, those things remain essentially </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">fixed regardless of how </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">circumstances </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">then change. Thus, for example, the free standing converter (a rewarded succeeder) may not always be ‘outstanding’, or a sponsored academy created from the forced conversion of a struggling school may later do well. Bu</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">t the governance/legal models are not able to accommodate that. In each case, the structure is that which was considered appropriate to the circumstances of the time of creation.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">For completeness I note that some commentators, such as Lord Adonis, have sug</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">gested (for example) allowing academies to change sponsor. That misunderstands the position of the academy and the sponsor –they are legally the same thing: the position is not comparable to that of a maintained school (which has its own legal identity) an</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">d the local authority which maintains it.</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> An academy can no more ‘change sponsor’ than a branch of Sainsburys can decide it wants to become a branch of Tesco.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">But regardless of those complexities, the fact that legal oversight is through the Funding Agreem</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">ent with the Secretary of State (who, in practice, delegates that to civil servants or agencies) has led to a process which is notable for its lack of transparency and openness. One particular issue is that the legal levers involved are those in the Fundin</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">g Agreement (with different funding agreements being differently framed) and they are generally ‘nuclear’ (in the sense that the Secretary of State is forced – in effect - to threaten contract termination to secure changes of performance). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“The functions </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in sup</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">port for schools at this level;”</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">At the moment there is a clear disconnect between the strategic statutory obligations on local authorities (eg in relation to ensuring sufficient suitable school places in their area) and their ability to discharge those ob</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">ligations. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Local authorities are thus held accountable (particularly in the eyes of the public) but without the ability to take action, whether that is to set up new schools or (in the case of academies/free schools) act on quality concerns.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Nor is that accountability gap filled by ‘sponsors’ or ‘chains’ which are rarely locally based, and do not in any event operate in an open, transparent or publicly accountable manner. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">And the consequence of the legal underpinning of academies (namely cont</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">racts which are made on the basis of an ever-changing model) means that the Secretary of State is effectively powerless to introduce changes across all schools (eg in relation to school meal standards) without primary legislation (as currently contemplated</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt"> by the Children and Families Bill 2013 in relation to children with SEN at academies).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements;”</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">Academy chains do not seem at all accountable other than (at most) to the Secretary of State direct (i.e. through the Funding Agreement). They are not even directly under the scrutiny of Ofsted or similar, let alone any wider public scrutiny.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">There is als</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">o, as above, the fact that an academy has no legal existence separate from the chain so there is no direct route to a change of chain or sponsor. Where (in limited circumstances) that has happened it has (I assume) been through contractual renegotiations o</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">r ‘novation’ (i.e. substitution of contract parties) of the Funding Agreement – private law routes ill-suited to dealing with public bodies/processes of this kind.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply; a</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">nd what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole;”</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">No comment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">“What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools.”</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">No </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">comment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>